9 An Act relating to transfer-on-death deeds; amending
58 O.S. 2021, Section 1252, as amended by Section 1,
10 Chapter 101, O.S.L. 2023 (58 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section
1252), which relates to acceptance by designated
11 grantee beneficiary; modifying procedures for
affidavits to accept certain property; modifying time
12 limitation for acceptance of certain property;
providing procedure if transfer-on-death deed is not
13 claimed within certain time period after death of
record owner; requiring certain notice; and providing
14 an effective date.
15
16
17 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
18 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 58 O.S. 2021, Section 1252, as
19 amended by Section 1, Chapter 101, O.S.L. 2023 (58 O.S. Supp. 2025,
20 Section 1252), is amended to read as follows:
21 Section 1252. A. An interest in real estate may be titled in
22 transfer-on-death form by recording a deed, signed by the record
23 owner of the interest, designating a grantee beneficiary or
24 beneficiaries of the interest. The deed shall transfer ownership of
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB3500 SFLR Page 1
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 the interest upon the death of the owner. A transfer-on-death deed
2 need not be supported by consideration. For purposes of the
3 Nontestamentary Transfer of Property Act, an “interest in real
4 estate” means any estate or interest in, over or under land,
5 including surface, minerals, structures and fixtures.
6 B. The signature, consent or agreement of or notice to a
7 grantee beneficiary or beneficiaries of a transfer-on-death deed
8 shall not be required for any purpose during the lifetime of the
9 record owner.
10 C. A designated grantee beneficiary may accept real estate
11 pursuant to a transfer-on-death deed only on behalf of himself,
12 herself, or a legal entity over which he or she has proper
13 authority. A beneficiary shall not accept such real estate on
14 behalf of another designated beneficiary.
15 D. Each designated grantee beneficiary wishing to accept real
16 estate pursuant to a transfer-on-death deed shall execute an
17 affidavit affirming:
18 1. Verification of the record owner’s death;
19 2. Whether the record owner and the designated beneficiary were
20 married at the time of the record owner’s death; and
21 3. A legal description of the real estate.
22 E. The Each designated grantee beneficiary shall attach sign
23 and record an affidavit and a copy of the record owner’s death
24 certificate to the beneficiary affidavit. For a record owner’s
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB3500 SFLR Page 2
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 deat h occurring on or after November 1, 2011, the beneficiary shall
2 record the affidavit and related documents with the office of the
3 county clerk where the real estate is located within nine (9) months
4 of the grantor’s death, otherwise the interest in the property
5 reverts to the deceased grantor’s estate; provided, however, for a
6 record owner’s death occurring before November 1, 2011, such
7 recording of the affidavit and related documents by the beneficiary
8 shall not be subject to the nine-month time limitation acknowledging
9 the beneficiary’s acceptance of the interest in the real estate. A
10 beneficiary may only accept real estate on his or her own behalf;
11 provided, however, multiple beneficiaries may sign the same
12 affidavit. The affidavit may be filed at any time after the death
13 of the record owner provided that the presentment date for creditors
14 has not passed for the estate of the record owner as provided in
15 subsection F of this section. Notwithstanding the provisions of
16 Section 26 of Title 16 of the Oklahoma Statutes, an affidavit
17 properly sworn to before a notary shall be received for record and
18 recorded by the county clerk without having been acknowledged and,
19 when recorded, shall be effective as if it had been acknowledged.
20 F. If no designated grantee beneficiary claims the real estate
21 within one (1) year of the death of the record owner, such property
22 may be included in an estate of the record owner opened pursuant to
23 Title 58 of the Oklahoma Statutes. Notice shall be provided to all
24 named beneficiaries of the deed in the manner required by the
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB3500 SFLR Page 3
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 prob ate procedure for a known creditor of the estate. Any unclaimed
2 interest remaining at the expiration of the presentment date for
3 creditor claims in the probate of the estate of the record owner
4 shall be forfeited and barred from being claimed by the named
5 beneficiary and the unclaimed interest shall become property of the
6 estate. If an estate of the record owner is opened for probate
7 prior to the one-year anniversary of the date of death of the record
8 owner, the personal representative shall be required to provide a
9 new notice to each unclaimed beneficiary at his or her last-known
10 address, or if an unclaimed beneficiary's address is unknown or the
11 unclaimed beneficiary has died after the record owner but prior to
12 acceptance, then by publication in one issue of a newspaper in the
13 county in which the property is located. The unclaimed interest
14 shall not be forfeited to the estate until thirty (30) days after
15 the mailing of notice or the publication of notice in the newspaper.
16 Upon the expiration of such period, the unclaimed interest shall
17 become property of the estate.
18 G. A beneficiary affidavit recorded pursuant to this section
19 before November 1, 2023, in which one or more, but not all, named
20 beneficiaries of a transfer-on-death deed explicitly accepts the
21 interests being conveyed by the deed on behalf of all or some of the
22 beneficiaries named therein shall be effective to accept such
23 interests if executed by at least one of the named beneficiaries
24 accepting such interests.
